  "texts": [
    "(2.19) can be solved by adopting a Newton-Raphson scheme, the inverse deflection angle β(n) can be iteratively calculated through [31] β (i+1) (n) = β (i) (n) -M -1 (n + β (i) (n)) • [β (i) (n) + α(n + β (i) (n))],(2.21)where M (n) is the magnification matrix, defined from the sphere's metric g ab, asM ab (n) = g ab + ∇ a α b (n).",
    "(2.22)We can then remap the observed map with the estimated inverse deflection angle in order to estimate the primary map.",
    "Delensing BiasIn this section, we will explore the biases introduced by the delensing procedure and suggest methods for their correction, known as debiasing.Debiasing is necessary for obtaining an accurate measurement of r. We posit that the biases detailed below are distinct from the delensing biases stemming from mode overlap between the B-field to be delensed and the B-field utilized for reconstructing the lensing potential, as detailed in studies such as [32] and [33].",
    "In these references, some bias terms were observed due to the overlap during the calculation of the power spectrum of the delensed B-mode, leading to a proven underestimation of the delensed B power.",
    "In our subsequent derivation, we solely focus on separating each component contributing to the delensing residuals (biases), without considering the B-mode overlap mentioned above."
  ]
}